''[[Sinclair Programs]]'' said that "the adventure itself is excellent, with enough puzzles appearing immediately to keep any adventurer involved and intrigued".<ref name="SP">{{Cite web |date=February 1985 |title=QuestProbe {{!}} Sinclair Programs |url=https://ia800604.us.archive.org/view_archive.php?archive=/1/items/World_of_Spectrum_June_2017_Mirror/World%20of%20Spectrum%20June%202017%20Mirror.zip&file=World%20of%20Spectrum%20June%202017%20Mirror/sinclair/magazines/SinclairPrograms/Issue8502/Pages/SinclairPrograms850200015.jpg |access-date=2021-10-12 |website=us.archive.org}}</ref>

''[[Personal Computer Games]]'' said that "the game is initially somewhat easier than ''The Hulk'', but rapidly becomes very challenging. The White Wizard is currently deeply involved and urges other adventurers to join him".<ref name="PCG">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/personalcomputergames-magazine-15/page/n79/mode/2up|title=Personal Computer Games Magazine Issue 15|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

''Home Computing Weekly'' wrote: "Classy, but rather over-priced: recommended for masochists and adventure freaks!"<ref name="HCW">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/home-computing-weekly-096/page/n41/mode/2up|title=Home Computing Weekly Magazine Issue 096|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

Paul Bond for ''[[Your Computer (British magazine)|Your Computer]]'' wrote: "Spider-man is the second adventure in the Questprobe series, a combination of comics and computer adventure games that allow you to become your favourite Marvel superhero".<ref name="YC">{{Cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/your-computer-magazine-1985-04/page/n48/mode/2up|title=Your Computer Magazine (April 1985)|date=April 16, 1985|via=Internet Archive}}</ref>

